## IP Address (Internet Protocol)

An IP address is a logical identifier used to identify a device on a network during communication.

### Key Points
- IPv4 addresses consist of 4 octets (e.g., 192.168.1.1)
- Each octet ranges from 0 to 255
- IP addresses can be static (fixed) or dynamic (change over time)
- Two devices cannot use the same IP address on the same network at the same time

### Types of IP Addresses

Public IP:
- Used to identify a device on the internet
- Assigned by an Internet Service Provider (ISP)
- Must be globally unique

Private IP:
- Used within local networks (home, office, internal systems)
- Not accessible directly from the internet
- Common ranges include:
  - 192.168.x.x
  - 10.x.x.x
  - 172.16–31.x.x

---

## MAC Address (Media Access Control)

A MAC address is a physical identifier assigned to a network interface card (NIC).

### Key Points
- Consists of 12 hexadecimal characters (e.g., 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E)
- The first 6 characters represent the manufacturer (OUI)
- The last 6 characters uniquely identify the device
- Used for communication within a local network (Layer 2)

---

## MAC Spoofing

MAC spoofing is the act of changing a device’s MAC address to impersonate another device.

### Common Uses
- Bypassing network restrictions
- Impersonating trusted devices
- Privacy or anonymity
- Security testing (ethical hacking)

---

## Summary

- IP Address: Identifies a device on a network for communication (logical)
- MAC Address: Identifies the physical device on a network (hardware)
- MAC Spoofing: Technique used to impersonate another device by altering the MAC address
