# ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)

ARP is used to link an IP address to a MAC address on a network.

Each device keeps a table called an ARP cache.
This stores IP and MAC address mappings of other devices.

## How ARP works

When a device wants to communicate with another device:
- It first checks its ARP cache
- If the MAC address is not found, it sends a broadcast

## ARP Request
A message sent to all devices on the network:
"Who has this IP address?"

## ARP Reply
The device with that IP responds:
"I have that IP, here is my MAC address"

## What happens next
- The sender stores the mapping in its ARP cache
- Future communication is faster

## Key Points
- Works only on a local network (LAN)
- Uses broadcasting
- Helps devices find each other
